# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oncogenes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] All living organisms are the products of repeated rounds of cell growth and division.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] During this process, known as the cell cycle, a cell duplicates its contents and then divides in two.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The purpose of the cell cycle is to accurately duplicate each organism's DNA and then divide the cell and its contents evenly between the two resulting cells.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Compared to the eukaryotic cell cycle, the prokaryotic cell cycle (known as binary fission) is relatively simple and quick: the chromosome replicates from the origin of replication, a new membrane is assembled, and the cell wall forms a septum which divides the cell into two.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] As the eukaryotic cell cycle is a complex process, eukaryotes have evolved a network of regulatory proteins, known as the **cell cycle control system**, which monitors and dictates the progression of the cell through the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This system acts like a timer, or a clock, which sets a fixed amount of time for the cell to spend in each phase of the cell cycle, while at the same time it also responds to information received from the processes it controls.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The cell cycle checkpoints play an important role in the control system by sensing defects that occur during essential processes such as DNA replication or chromosome segregation, and inducing a cell cycle arrest in response until the defects are repaired.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Those complexes, in turn, activate different downstream targets to promote or prevent cell cycle progression.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The G1 checkpoint, also known as the restriction point in mammalian cells and the start point in yeast, is the point at which the cell becomes committed to entering the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] As the cell progresses through G1, depending on internal and external conditions, it can either delay G1, enter a quiescent state known as G0, or proceed past the restriction point.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] DNA damage is the main indication for a cell to "restrict" and not enter the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The decision to commit to a new round of cell division occurs when the cell activates cyclin-CDK-dependent transcription which promotes entry into S phase.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This check point ensures the further process.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] During early G1, there are three transcriptional repressors, known as pocket proteins, that bind to E2F transcription factors.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The E2F gene family is a group of transcription factors that target many genes that are important for control of the cell cycle, including cyclins, CDKs, checkpoint regulators, and DNA repair proteins.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Misregulation of the E2F family is often found in cancer cases, providing evidence that the E2F family is essential for the tight regulation of DNA replication and division.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The three pocket proteins are Retinoblastoma (Rb), p107, and p130, which bind to the E2F transcription factors to prevent progression past the G1 checkpoint.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The E2F gene family contains some proteins with activator mechanisms and some proteins with repressing mechanisms.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] P107 and p130 act as co-repressors for E2F 4 and E2F 5, which work to repress transcription of G1-to-S promoting factors.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The third pocket protein, Rb, binds to and represses E2F 1, E2F 2, and E2F 3, which are the E2F proteins with activating abilities.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Positive feedback plays an essential role in regulating the progression from G1 to S phase, particularly involving the phosphorylation of Rb by a Cyclin/CDK protein complex.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Rb without a phosphate, or unphosphorylated Rb, regulates G0 cell cycle exit and differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] During the beginning of the G1 phase, growth factors and DNA damage signal for the rise of cyclin D levels, which then binds to Cdk4 and Cdk6 to form the CyclinD:Cdk4/6 complex.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This complex is known to inactivate Rb by phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] However, the details of Rb phosphorylation are quite complex and specific compared to previous knowledge about the G1checkpoint.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] CyclinD:Cdk4/6 places only one phosphate, or monophosphorylates, Rb at one of its fourteen accessible and unique phosphorylation sites.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Each of the fourteen specific mono-phosphorylated isoforms has a differential binding preference to E2F family members, which likely adds to the diversity of cellular processes within the mammalian body.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] E2F 4 and E2F 5 are dependent on p107 and p130 to maintain their nuclear localization.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] However, Cyclin D:Cdk 4/6 also phosphorylates p107 and p130, a process which releases their bind from E2F 4 and 5 (which then escape to the cytoplasm), and allowing for E2F 1–3 to bind to the DNA and initiate transcription of Cyclin E.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Rb proteins maintain their mono-phosphorylated state during early G1 phase, while Cyclin E is accumulating and binding to Cdk2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] CyclinE:Cdk2 plays an additional important phosphorylation role in the G1-to-S transition.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Particularly, CyclinE:Cdk2 promotes a positive feedback loop which creates an "all or nothing" switch.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] In many genetic control networks, positive feedback ensures that cells do not slip back and forth between cell cycle phases Cyclin E:Cdk2 proceeds to phosphorylate Rb at all of its phosphorylation sites, also termed "hyper-phosphorylate", which ensures complete inactivation of Rb.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The hyper phosphorylation of Rb is considered the late G1 restriction point, after which the cell cannot go backwards in the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At this point, E2F 1-3 proteins bind to DNA and transcribe Cyclin A and Cdc 6.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 1B (CDKN1B), also known as p27, binds to and prevents the activation of CyclinE:Cdk2 by inhibition.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] However, as Cyclin A accumulates and binds to Cdk2, they form a complex and inhibit p27.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The G1 phase cyclin-dependent kinase works together with S phase cyclin-dependent kinase targeting p27 for degradation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] In turn, this allows for full activation of Cyclin A:Cdk2, a complex which phosphorylates E2F 1-3 initiating their disassociation from the DNA promoter sites.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This allows E2F 6–8 to bind to the DNA and inhibit transcription.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The negative feedback loop used to successfully inhibit the inhibitor, p27, is another essential process used by cells to ensure mono-directional movement and no backtrack through the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] When DNA damage occurs, or when the cell detects any defects which necessitate it to delay or halt the cell cycle in G1, arrest occurs through several mechanisms.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The rapid response involves phosphorylation events that initiate with either kinase ATM (Ataxia telangiectasia mutated) or ATR (Ataxia Telangiectasia and Rad3 related), which act as sensors, depending on the type of damage.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] These kinases phosphorylate and activate the effector kinases Chk2 and Chk1, respectively, which in turn phosphorylate the phosphatase Cdc25A, thus marking it for ubiquitination and degradation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] As Cdc25A activates the previously mentioned cyclin E-CDK2 complex by removing inhibitory phosphates from CDK2, in the absence of Cdc25A, cyclin E-CDK2 remains inactive, and the cell remains in G1.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] To maintain the arrest, another response is initiated, by which Chk2 or Chk1 phosphorylate p53, a tumor suppressor, and this stabilizes p53 by preventing it from binding Mdm2, a ubiquitin ligase which inhibits p53 by targeting it for degradation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The stable p53 then acts a transcriptional activator of several target genes, including p21, an inhibitor of the G1-to-S promoting complex cyclin E-CDK2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Recently, some aspects of this model have been disputed.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Following DNA replication in S phase, the cell undergoes a growth phase known as G2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] During this time, necessary mitotic proteins are produced and the cell is once more subjected to regulatory mechanisms to ensure proper status for entry into the proliferative Mitotic (M) phase.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Multiple mechanistic checkpoints are involved in this transition from G2 to M, with a common uniting factor of cyclin-Cdk activity.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Although variations in requisite cyclin-Cdk complexes exist across organisms, the necessity of the kinase activity is conserved and typically focuses on a single pairing.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] In fission yeast three different forms of mitotic cyclin exist, and six in budding yeast, yet the primary cyclin utilized is cyclin B.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Cyclin B will serve as reference for discussion of the G2/M checkpoint transition.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Similar to S Phase, G2 experiences a DNA damage checkpoint.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The cell is once more examined for sites of DNA damage or incomplete replication, and the kinases ATR and ATM are recruited to damage sites.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Activation of Chk1 and Chk2 also transpire, as well as p53 activation, to induce cell cycle arrest and halt progression into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] An additional component of S phase, the Pre-Replicative Complex, must be inactivated via cyclin B-Cdk1 phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] As these previous checkpoints are assessed, G2 protein accumulation serves to activate cyclin B-Cdk1 activity via multiple mechanisms.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] CyclinA-Cdk2 activates Cdc25, an activator of cyclin B-Cdk1, which then deactivates the cyclin B-Cdk1 inhibitor, Wee1.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This results in a positive feedback loop, significantly increasing cyclin B expression and Cdk1 activation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] As the cell progresses through G2 and reaches the G2/M transition, the kinase Plk1 phosphorylates Wee1, which targets Wee1 for degradation via the SCF ubiquitin ligase complex.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] An additional function of Plk1 is to activate Cdc25 through phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The compound effect of Wee1 degradation and Cdc25 activation is the net removal of inhibitory phosphorylation from cdc2, which activates cdc2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Plk1 is activated at the G2/M transition by the Aurora A and Bora, which accumulate during G2 and form an activation complex.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The Plk1-Cdc2-cdc25 complex then initiates a positive feedback loop which serves to further activate Cdc2, and in conjunction with an increase in cyclin B levels during G2, the resulting cdc2-cyclin B complexes then activate downstream targets which promote entry into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The resultant Cdk1 activity also activates expression of Mem1-Fkh, a G2/M transition gene.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The rapid surge in cyclin B-Cdk1 activity is necessary, as M phase initiation is an all-or-nothing event engaging in hysteresis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Hysteresis of Cdk1 activity via cyclin B drives M phase entry by establishing a minimum threshold of cyclin B concentration.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This exists at a level higher than the minimum needed for the continuation of M phase after entry, acting to safeguard the all-or-nothing event.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This entry concentration is further increased in the case of incomplete DNA replication, adding another regulatory mechanism at the G2/M transition point.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The presence of hysteresis allows for M phase entry to be highly regulated as a function of cyclin B-Cdk1 activity.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The mechanisms by which mitotic entry is prevented in response to DNA damage are similar to those in the G1/S checkpoint.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] DNA damage triggers the activation of the aforementioned ATM/ATR pathway, in which ATM/ATR phosphorylate and activate the Chk1/Chk2 checkpoint kinases.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Chk1/2 phosphorylate cdc25 which, in addition to being inhibited, is also sequestered in the cytoplasm by the 14-3-3 proteins.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] 14-3-3 are upregulated by p53, which, as previously mentioned, is activated by Chk1 and ATM/ATR. p53 also transactivates p21, and both p21 and the 14-3-3 in turn inhibit cyclin B-cdc2 complexes through the phosphorylation and cytoplasmic sequestering of cdc2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] In addition, the inactivation of cdc25 results in its inability to dephosphorylate and activate cdc2.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Finally, another mechanism of damage response is through the negative regulation of Plk1 by ATM/ATR, which in turn results in the stabilization of Wee1 and Myt1, which can then phosphorylate and inhibit cdc2, thus keeping the cell arrested in G2 until the damage is fixed.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At the end of G2, the cell transitions into mitosis, where the nucleus divides.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The G2 to M transition is dramatic; there is an all-or-nothing effect, and the transition is irreversible.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This is advantageous to the cell because entering mitosis is a critical step in the life cycle of a cell.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] If it does not fully commit, the cell would run into many issues with partially dividing, ultimately likely leading to the cell's death.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] In frog oocytes, the signal cascade is induced when progesterone binds to a membrane bound receptor.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Mos then phosphorylates MEK1, which phosphorylates MAPK.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] MAPK serves two roles: activating the Cyclin B-Cdk1 complex to initiate entrance into mitosis and activating Mos .
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The activation of Mos leads to a positive feedback loop and therefore acts as "toggle switch" to create the all-or-nothing entrance into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This feedback loop was first found by showing that MAPK-P (phosphorylated MAPK) concentrations increased in response to increasing levels of progesterone.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At the single cell level, each cell either had entirely phosphorylated MAPK or no phosphorylated MAPK, confirming that it acts as a switch-like mechanism in each cell.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] It was additionally shown that blocking Mos protein synthesis makes the MAPK-P responses more graded, showing that Mos protein synthesis is necessary for the all-or-none character of MAPK activation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] This process can be understood using unstability.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Using the graph shown to the right, the Mos synthesis rate shifts as more progesterone is added.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] With each curve, there are stable fixed points and unstable fixed points.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At the unstable fixed points, the system will push toward either one of the stable fixed points.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] So, the system can either be in the "on" state or the "off" state, not in between.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] When the progesterone level is high enough, the Mos curve is shifted higher and ultimately intersects the degradation line at only one point, so there is only one stable "on" state, indicating the entrance into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The irreversibility we see in the Mitosis transition point comes from having high enough levels of progesterone in the cell.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At high enough levels of progesterone, the system is monostable as a result of the positive feedback loop between Mapk and Mos.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The point at which the system switches from bistable to monostable is called the saddle node bifurcation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] So, we can understand the all-or-nothing, irreversible response of the mitotic transition with a mathematical model of the molecular regulators as a bistable system that depends on the existence of positive feedback.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The "off-state" is annihilated by a high enough level of progesterone and once the cell gets pushed past the off-state, it is then stuck in the on-state.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Coming from this bi-stable model, we can understand the mitotic transition as relying on hysteresis to drive it.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Hysteresis is defined as the dependence of the state of a system on its history.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The Novak–Tyson model is a mathematical model of cell cycle progression that predicts that irreversible transitions entering and exiting mitosis are driven by hysteresis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Unreplicated DNA raises the level of cyclin necessary for Cdc2 activation and therefore entrance into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] There is a decrease in the rate of Cdc2 activation at concentrations of cyclin B just above the activation threshold.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Sha et al. did experiments in *Xenopus laevis* egg extracts in 2003 to demonstrate this hysteretic nature.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Using cycling extracts, they observed that the activation threshold for Δcyclin B is between 32 and 42 nM whereas the inactivation threshold is between 16 and 24 nM Δcyclin B.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Therefore, these experiments confirmed the bistability of this system and the importance of hysteresis in this cell cycle transition.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] At the intermediate cyclin B concentrations, either the interphase or mitotic state of the cell is possible.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Since entering mitosis is a large and costly commitment for the cell, it is logical that systems would be in place to prevent premature entrance into this step.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] It has been shown that mistakes in previous steps, such as having unreplicated sections of DNA blocks progression in the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The Novak–Tyson model predicts this occurs via raising the level of cyclin B necessary for entrance into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Sha et al. investigated whether this was true in *Xenopus* egg extracts.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] They used aphidicolin (APH) to inhibit DNA polymerase and prevent DNA replication.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] When treated with Cyclin B in interphase, the threshold of activation increased to between 80 and 100 nM, as predicted by the Novak–Tyson model.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] So, these experiments confirm that the stress of unreplicated DNA in the cell affect the hysteresis loop and result in a much higher cyclin B threshold to enter into mitosis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The mitotic spindle checkpoint occurs at the point in metaphase where all the chromosomes should/have aligned at the mitotic plate and be under bipolar tension.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The tension created by this bipolar attachment is what is sensed, which initiates the anaphase entry.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] To do this, the sensing mechanism ensures that the anaphase-promoting complex (APC/C) is no longer inhibited, which is now free to degrade cyclin B, which harbors a D-box (destruction box), and to break down securin.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The latter is a protein whose function is to inhibit separase, which in turn cuts the cohesins, the protein composite responsible for cohesion of sister chromatids.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Once this inhibitory protein is degraded via ubiquitination and subsequent proteolysis, separase then causes sister chromatid separation.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] After the cell has split into its two daughter cells, the cell enters G1.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] DNA repair processes and cell cycle checkpoints have been intimately linked with cancer due to their functions regulating genome stability and cell progression, respectively.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The precise molecular mechanisms that connect dysfunctions in these pathways to the onset of particular cancers are not well understood in most cases.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] The loss of ATM has been shown to precede lymphoma development presumably due to excessive homologous recombination, leading to high genomic instability.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Disruption of Chk1 in mice led significant misregulation of cell cycle checkpoints, an accumulation of DNA damage, and an increased incidence of tumorigenesis.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] Single mutant inheritance of BRCA1 or BRCA2 predisposes females toward breast and ovarian cancers.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] BRCA1 is known to be required for S and G2/M transitions, and is involved in the cellular response to DNA damage.
[src:oncogenes/cell-cycle-checkpoint] BRCA2 is believed to be involved in homologous recombination and regulating the S-phase checkpoint, and mutations of deficiencies in BRCA2 are strongly linked to tumorigenesis.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In cancer, *c-myc* is often constitutively (persistently) expressed.
[src:oncogenes/myc] This leads to the increased expression of many genes, some of which are involved in cell proliferation, contributing to the formation of cancer.
[src:oncogenes/myc] A common human translocation involving *c-myc* is critical to the development of most cases of Burkitt lymphoma.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Constitutive upregulation of *Myc* genes have also been observed in carcinoma of the cervix, colon, breast, lung and stomach.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc is thus viewed as a promising target for anti-cancer drugs.
[src:oncogenes/myc] c-Myc also plays an important role in stem cell biology and was one of the original Yamanaka factors used to reprogram somatic cells into induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In the human genome, *c-myc* is located on chromosome 8 and is believed to regulate expression of 15% of all genes through binding on enhancer box sequences (E-boxes).
[src:oncogenes/myc] In addition to its role as a classical transcription factor, *N-myc* may recruit histone acetyltransferases (HATs).
[src:oncogenes/myc] This allows it to regulate global chromatin structure via histone acetylation.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The *Myc* family was first established after discovery of homology between an oncogene carried by the Avian **v**irus, **My**elo**c**ytomatosis (*v-myc*; P10395) and a human gene over-expressed in various cancers, **c**ellular Myc (*c-Myc*).
[src:oncogenes/myc] Later, discovery of further homologous genes in humans led to the addition of *n-Myc* and *l-Myc* to the family of genes.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The most frequently discussed example of *c-Myc* as a proto-oncogene is its implication in Burkitt's lymphoma.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In Burkitt's lymphoma, cancer cells show chromosomal translocations, most commonly between chromosome 8 and chromosome 14 [t(8;14)].
[src:oncogenes/myc] This causes *c-Myc* to be placed downstream of the highly active immunoglobulin (Ig) promoter region, leading to overexpression of *Myc*.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The protein products of *Myc* family genes all belong to the Myc family of transcription factors, which contain bHLH (basic helix-loop-helix) and LZ (leucine zipper) structural motifs.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The bHLH motif allows Myc proteins to bind with DNA, while the leucine zipper TF-binding motif allows dimerization with Max, another bHLH transcription factor.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc mRNA contains an IRES (internal ribosome entry site) that allows the RNA to be translated into protein when 5' cap-dependent translation is inhibited, such as during viral infection.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc proteins are transcription factors that activate expression of many pro-proliferative genes through binding enhancer box sequences (E-boxes) and recruiting histone acetyltransferases (HATs).
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc is thought to function by upregulating transcript elongation of actively transcribed genes through the recruitment of transcriptional elongation factors.
[src:oncogenes/myc] It can also act as a transcriptional repressor.
[src:oncogenes/myc] By binding Miz-1 transcription factor and displacing the p300 co-activator, it inhibits expression of Miz-1 target genes.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In addition, myc has a direct role in the control of DNA replication.
[src:oncogenes/myc] This activity could contribute to DNA amplification in cancer cells.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc is activated upon various mitogenic signals such as serum stimulation or by Wnt, Shh and EGF (via the MAPK/ERK pathway).
[src:oncogenes/myc] By modifying the expression of its target genes, Myc activation results in numerous biological effects.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Nucleotide metabolism genes are upregulated by Myc, which are necessary for Myc induced proliferation or cell growth.
[src:oncogenes/myc] There have been several studies that have clearly indicated Myc's role in cell competition.
[src:oncogenes/myc] A major effect of c-myc is B cell proliferation, and gain of MYC has been associated with B cell malignancies and their increased aggressiveness, including histological transformation.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In B cells, Myc acts as a classical oncogene by regulating a number of pro-proliferative and anti-apoptotic pathways, this also includes tuning of BCR signaling and CD40 signaling in regulation of microRNAs (miR-29, miR-150, miR-17-92).
[src:oncogenes/myc] c-Myc induces MTDH (AEG-1) gene expression and in turn itself requires AEG-1 oncogene for its expression.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc-nick is a cytoplasmic form of Myc produced by a partial proteolytic cleavage of full-length c-Myc and N-Myc.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc cleavage is mediated by the calpain family of calcium-dependent cytosolic proteases.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The cleavage of Myc by calpains is a constitutive process but is enhanced under conditions that require rapid downregulation of Myc levels, such as during terminal differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Upon cleavage, the C-terminus of Myc (containing the DNA binding domain) is degraded, while Myc-nick, the N-terminal segment 298-residue segment remains in the cytoplasm.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc-nick contains binding domains for histone acetyltransferases and for ubiquitin ligases.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The functions of Myc-nick are currently under investigation, but this new Myc family member was found to regulate cell morphology, at least in part, by interacting with acetyl transferases to promote the acetylation of α-tubulin.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Ectopic expression of Myc-nick accelerates the differentiation of committed myoblasts into muscle cells.
[src:oncogenes/myc] A large body of evidence shows that Myc genes and proteins are highly relevant for treating tumors.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Except for early response genes, Myc universally upregulates gene expression.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Furthermore, the upregulation is nonlinear.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Genes for which expression is already significantly upregulated in the absence of Myc are strongly boosted in the presence of Myc, whereas genes for which expression is low in the absence Myc get only a small boost when Myc is present.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Inactivation of SUMO-activating enzyme (SAE1 / SAE2) in the presence of Myc hyperactivation results in mitotic catastrophe and cell death in cancer cells.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Hence inhibitors of SUMOylation may be a possible treatment for cancer.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Amplification of the MYC gene was found in a significant number of epithelial ovarian cancer cases.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In TCGA datasets, the amplification of Myc occurs in several cancer types, including breast, colorectal, pancreatic, gastric, and uterine cancers.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In the experimental transformation process of normal cells into cancer cells, the MYC gene can cooperate with the RAS gene.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Expression of Myc is highly dependent on BRD4 function in some cancers.
[src:oncogenes/myc] BET inhibitors have been used to successfully block Myc function in pre-clinical cancer models and are currently being evaluated in clinical trials.
[src:oncogenes/myc] MYC expression is controlled by a wide variety of noncoding RNAs, including miRNA, lncRNA, and circRNA.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Some of these RNAs have been shown to be specific for certain types of human tissues and tumors.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Changes in the expression of such RNAs can potentially be used to develop targeted tumor therapy.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Fluorescence *in situ* hybridization (FISH) has become a routine practice in many clinical laboratories for lymphoma characterization.
[src:oncogenes/myc] A break-apart (BAP) FISH probe is commonly utilized for the detection of *MYC*-R due to the variability of breakpoints in the *MYC* locus and the diversity of rearrangement partners, including immunoglobulin (IG) and non-IG partners (i.e.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The *MYC* BAP probe includes a red and a green probe which hybridize 5' and 3' to the *MYC* gen, respectively.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In an intact *MYC* locus, these probes yield a fusion signal.
[src:oncogenes/myc] There is a large variability in the interpretation of unbalanced *MYC* BAP results among the scientists, which can impact diagnostic classification and therapeutic management of the patients.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In Drosophila Myc is encoded by the diminutive locus, (which was known to geneticists prior to 1935).
[src:oncogenes/myc] Classical diminutive alleles resulted in a viable animal with small body size.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Drosophila has subsequently been used to implicate Myc in cell competition, endoreplication, and cell growth.
[src:oncogenes/myc] During the discovery of Myc gene, it was realized that chromosomes that reciprocally translocate to chromosome 8 contained immunoglobulin genes at the break-point.
[src:oncogenes/myc] To study the mechanism of tumorigenesis in Burkitt lymphoma by mimicking expression pattern of Myc in these cancer cells, transgenic mouse models were developed.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Myc gene placed under the control of IgM heavy chain enhancer in transgenic mice gives rise to mainly lymphomas.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Later on, in order to study effects of Myc in other types of cancer, transgenic mice that overexpress Myc in different tissues (liver, breast) were also made.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In all these mouse models overexpression of Myc causes tumorigenesis, illustrating the potency of Myc oncogene.
[src:oncogenes/myc] In a study with mice, reduced expression of Myc was shown to induce longevity, with significantly extended median and maximum lifespans in both sexes and a reduced mortality rate across all ages, better health, cancer progression was slower, better metabolism and they had smaller bodies.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Also, Less TOR, AKT, S6K and other changes in energy and metabolic pathways (such as AMPK, more oxygen consumption, more body movements, etc.).
[src:oncogenes/myc] Sedivy and others used Cre-Loxp -recombinase to knockout one copy of Myc and this resulted in a "Haplo-insufficient" genotype noted as Myc±.
[src:oncogenes/myc] The phenotypes seen oppose the effects of normal aging and are shared with many other long-lived mouse models such as CR (calorie restriction) ames dwarf, rapamycin, metformin and resveratrol.
[src:oncogenes/myc] One study found that Myc and p53 genes were key to the survival of chronic myeloid leukaemia (CML) cells.
[src:oncogenes/myc] Targeting Myc and p53 proteins with drugs gave positive results on mice with CML.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] An **oncogene** is a gene that has the potential to cause cancer.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] In tumor cells, these genes are often mutated, or expressed at high levels.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Most normal cells undergo a preprogrammed rapid cell death (apoptosis) if critical functions are altered and then malfunction.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Activated oncogenes can cause those cells designated for apoptosis to survive and proliferate instead.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Most oncogenes began as **proto-oncogenes**, normal genes involved in cell growth and proliferation or inhibition of apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] If, through mutation, normal genes promoting cellular growth are up-regulated (gain-of-function mutation), they predispose the cell to cancer and are termed *oncogenes*.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Usually, multiple oncogenes, along with mutated apoptotic or tumor suppressor genes, act in concert to cause cancer.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Oncogenes are a physically and functionally diverse set of genes, and as a result, their protein products have pleiotropic effects on a variety of intricate regulatory cascades within the cell.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Since the 1970s, dozens of oncogenes have been identified in human cancer.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Many cancer drugs target the proteins encoded by oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The resultant protein encoded by an oncogene is termed **oncoprotein**.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Oncogenes play an important role in the regulation or synthesis of proteins linked to tumorigenic cell growth.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Some oncoproteins are accepted and used as tumor markers.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Genes known as **proto-oncogenes** are those that normally encourage cell growth and division in order to generate new cells or sustain the viability of pre-existing cells.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] When overexpressed, proto-oncogenes can be inadvertently activated (turned on), which changes them to oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] A person's genetic "coding" may differ in a way that causes an oncogene to always be activated.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Cells can frequently switch genes on or off via epigenetic mechanisms rather than actual genetic alterations.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Alternately, different chemical compounds that can be linked to genetic material (DNA or RNA) may have an impact on which genes are active.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] An oncogene may sporadically become activated due to these epigenetic modifications.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] A chromosome's DNA sequence may alter each time a cell divides.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] This could cause a gene to be located near to a proto-oncogene that acts as an "on" switch, keeping it active even when it shouldn't.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The cell can develop irregularly with the aid of this new oncogene.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] If one cell has more copies of a gene than another, that cell may produce too much of a certain protein.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The first human oncogene (HRAS), a crucial finding in the field of cancer research, was discovered in the early 1980s, and since then, the number of novel pathogenic oncogenes identified has increased steadily.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Investigating the quickly expanding field of oncogene molecular research, the goal of this special issue was to generate practical translational indicators that could be able to meet clinical needs.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Genes that are considered crucial for cancer can be divided into two categories based on whether the harmful mutations in them result in function loss or gain.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Gain-of-function mutations of proto-oncogenes drive cells to proliferate when they shouldn't, while loss-of-function mutations of tumor suppressor genes free cells from inhibitions that typically serve to control their numbers.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The ability of the mutant genes, known as oncogenes, to steer a specific line of test cells toward malignant proliferation can occasionally be used to identify these later mutations, which have a dominating effect.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Many of them were initially found to induce cancer in animals when they are introduced through viral infection, which carries an activated version of a proto-oncogene from a prior host cell (an oncovirus).
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Another method for identifying oncogenes is to look for genes that are activated by mutations in human cancer cells or by chromosomal translocations that may indicate the presence of a gene that is crucial for cancer.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Later on, the term "oncogene" was rediscovered in 1969 by National Cancer Institute scientists George Todaro and Robert Huebner.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The first confirmed oncogene was discovered in 1970 and was termed SRC (pronounced "sarc" as it is short for sarcoma).
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] SRC was first discovered as an oncogene in a chicken retrovirus.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Steve Martin of the University of California, Berkeley demonstrated that SRC was indeed the gene of the virus that acted as an oncogene upon infection.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The first nucleotide sequence of v-Src was sequenced in 1980 by A.P.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Varmus of the University of California, San Francisco demonstrated that oncogenes were activated proto-oncogenes as is found in many organisms, including humans.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Bishop and Varmus were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1989 for their discovery of the cellular origin of retroviral oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Robert Weinberg is credited with discovering the first identified human oncogene in a human bladder cancer cell line.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The molecular nature of the mutation leading to oncogenesis was subsequently isolated and characterized by the Spanish biochemist Mariano Barbacid and published in *Nature* in 1982.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Barbacid spent the following months extending his research, eventually discovering that the oncogene was a mutated allele of HRAS and characterizing its activation mechanism.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] A **proto-oncogene** is a normal gene that could become an oncogene due to mutations or increased expression.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Proto-oncogenes code for proteins that help to regulate the cell growth and differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Proto-oncogenes are often involved in signal transduction and execution of mitogenic signals, usually through their protein products.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Upon acquiring an activating mutation, a proto-oncogene becomes a tumor-inducing agent, an oncogene.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Examples of proto-oncogenes include RAS, WNT, MYC, ERK, and TRK.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The MYC gene is implicated in Burkitt's lymphoma, which starts when a chromosomal translocation moves an enhancer sequence within the vicinity of the MYC gene.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The MYC gene codes for widely used transcription factors.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] When the enhancer sequence is wrongly placed, these transcription factors are produced at much higher rates.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Another example of an oncogene is the Bcr-Abl gene found on the Philadelphia chromosome, a piece of genetic material seen in Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia caused by the translocation of pieces from chromosomes 9 and 22.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Bcr-Abl codes for a tyrosine kinase, which is constitutively active, leading to uncontrolled cell proliferation.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The proto-oncogene can become an oncogene by a relatively small modification of its original function.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] The expression of oncogenes can be regulated by microRNAs (miRNAs), small RNAs 21-25 nucleotides in length that control gene expression by downregulating them.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Mutations in such microRNAs (known as oncomirs) can lead to activation of oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Antisense messenger RNAs could theoretically be used to block the effects of oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] There are several systems for classifying oncogenes, but there is not yet a widely accepted standard.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] They are sometimes grouped both spatially (moving from outside the cell inwards) and chronologically (parallelling the "normal" process of signal transduction).
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Cancer patients are generally categorized according to clinical parameters in order to tailor their cancer therapy.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] For example, the separation of patients with acute leukemia into those with lymphocytic leukemia and those with myelocytic leukemia is important, because the optimal treatment for each form is different.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Even in a particular disease, the identification of patients with good and poor prognostic potential is helpful, since more aggressive therapy may be needed to achieve a cure in the poor prognostic group.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Oncogenes are prognostic markers in certain human cancers.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] N-myc amplification is an independent determinant in predicting a poor outcome in childhood neuroblastoma.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Those children with amplification of N-myc, regardless of stage, will have shortened survival.
[src:oncogenes/oncogene] Thus, therapeutic efforts are concentrated on intensifying treatment in this poor prognostic group.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The *TP53* gene is inactivated in a majority (>50%) of human cancer cases.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This can be caused by any various factors, including mutations in the gene, epigenetic events, or interactions with other proteins.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This association indicates that the *TP53* gene plays a crucial role in preventing cancer formation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] *TP53* gene encodes proteins that bind to DNA and regulate gene expression to prevent mutations of the genome.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In addition to the full-length protein, the human *TP53* gene encodes at least 12 protein isoforms.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Comparative genomic studies found pathogenic mutations absent in some Neanderthal populations, while modern humans exhibit an expansion of over 1,000 mutated variations.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Evidence suggests that the vast majority of these protein-coding variants arose very recently in human history, specifically concentrated within a window of 5,000 to 10,000 years ago.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In humans, the *TP53* gene is located on the short arm of chromosome 17 (17p13.1).
[src:oncogenes/p53] The gene spans 20 kb, with a non-coding exon 1 and a very long first intron of 10 kb, overlapping the Hp53int1 gene.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The coding sequence contains five regions showing a high degree of conservation in vertebrates, predominantly in exons 2, 5, 6, 7 and 8, but the sequences found in invertebrates show only distant resemblance to mammalian TP53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] *TP53* orthologs have been identified in most mammals for which complete genome data are available.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Elephants, with 20 genes for TP53, rarely get cancer.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A proline-rich domain (residues 64–92), involved in apoptotic function and nuclear export via MAPK signaling.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A central DNA-binding domain (DBD; residues 102–292), containing a zinc atom and multiple arginine residues, essential for sequence-specific DNA interaction and co-repressor binding such as LMO3.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A nuclear localization sequence (NLS; residues 316–325), required for nuclear import.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A homo-oligomerization domain (OD; residues 307–355), which mediates tetramerization—essential for p53 activity *in vivo*.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A C-terminal regulatory domain (residues 356–393), which modulates the DNA-binding activity of the central domain.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Most cancer-associated mutations in *TP53* occur in the DBD, impairing DNA binding and transcriptional activation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These are typically recessive loss-of-function mutations.
[src:oncogenes/p53] By contrast, mutations in the OD can exert dominant negative effects by forming inactive complexes with wild-type p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Wild-type p53 is a labile protein containing both folded and intrinsically disordered regions that act synergistically.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Although designated as a 53 kDa protein by SDS-PAGE, the actual molecular weight of p53α is 43.7 kDa.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The discrepancy is due to its high proline content, which slows electrophoretic migration.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 initially forms dimers cotranslationally during protein synthesis on ribosomes.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Each dimer consists of two p53 monomers joined through their oligomerization domains.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The dimerization interface spans residues 325–356 and includes a beta-strand (residues 325–333), a alpha-helix (residues 335–356), and a sharp turn at the conserved hinge residue Gly334.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This configuration links the beta-strand and alpha-helix to form a V-shaped monomer topology.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The beta-strand contributes to the formation of an antiparallel intermolecular beta-sheet between two p53 monomers, stabilized by hydrophobic interactions involving Phe328, Leu330, and Ile332.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The alpha-helix forms an antiparallel coiled-coil between the two monomers, with a packing angle of 156°.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Helix–helix interactions are stabilized by hydrophobic contacts (e.g., Phe338, Phe341, Leu344) and electrostatic interactions, such as the Arg337–Asp352 salt bridge.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Following dimer formation, p53 dimers associate posttranslationally to form tetramers (dimers of dimers).
[src:oncogenes/p53] The tetramerization domain (residues 325–356) plays a central role in stabilizing the tetrameric structure.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In the tetramer, the two primary dimers associate at an angle described as "roughly orthogonal," with a helix bundle packing angle (θ) of approximately 80°.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Tetramers represent the active form of p53 for DNA binding and transcriptional regulation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Like 95% of human genes, *TP53* encodes multiple proteins, collectively known as the **p53 isoforms**.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These vary in size from 3.5 to 43.7 kDa.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Isoform expression is tissue-dependent, and p53α is never expressed alone.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The isoforms differ by the inclusion or exclusion of specific domains.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Some, such as Δ133p53β/γ and Δ160p53α/β/γ, lack the transactivation or proline-rich domains and are deficient in apoptosis induction, illustrating the functional diversity of *TP53*.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 functions as a transcription factor by binding DNA as a tetramer, a structure that is essential for its stability and effective DNA binding activity.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Once bound to DNA, p53 induces the transcription of numerous genes involved in DNA repair pathways.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This includes components of base excision repair (BER) such as OGG1 and MUTYH, nucleotide excision repair (NER) factors like DDB2 and XPC, mismatch repair (MMR) genes such as MSH2 and MLH1, and elements of homologous recombination (HR) and non-homologous end-joining (NHEJ) repair.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These transcriptional responses are crucial for the DNA damage response (DDR), allowing cells to efficiently repair damaged DNA and maintain genomic integrity.
[src:oncogenes/p53] While p53's role is most clearly defined in transcriptional activation of repair genes, it also participates in non-transcriptional regulation of DNA repair processes, particularly in HR and NHEJ, by modulating protein interactions and chromatin accessibility.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 binds specific elements in the promoter of target genes, including CDKN1A, which encodes p21.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Upon activation by p53, p21 inhibits cyclin-dependent kinases, leading to cell cycle arrest and contributing to tumor suppression.
[src:oncogenes/p53] However, p21 can also be induced independently of p53 during processes such as differentiation, development, and in response to serum stimulation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p21 (WAF1) binds to cyclin-CDK complexes (notably CDK2, CDK1, CDK4, and CDK6), inhibiting their activity and blocking the G1/S transition.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This inhibition enforces a cell cycle pause that allows DNA repair to occur.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In cells with functional p53, p21 is upregulated in response to DNA damage, ensuring this checkpoint control.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In contrast, p53 mutations impair p21 induction and compromise this control.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In human embryonic stem cells (hESCs), although p21 mRNA is upregulated following DNA damage, the protein is not detectable.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This reflects a nonfunctional p53-p21 axis at the G1/S checkpoint.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This discrepancy is largely due to post-transcriptional repression, particularly by the miR-302 family of microRNAs, which inhibit p21 translation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Although p53 binds the CDKN1A promoter in hESCs, it does not regulate miR-302, which is constitutively expressed and suppresses p21 expression.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The p53 pathway is interconnected with the RB1 pathway via p14^ARF, which links the regulation of these key tumor suppressors.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 expression can be induced by UV radiation, which also causes DNA damage.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In this context, p53 activation can initiate processes that lead to melanin production and tanning.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Levels of p53 play an important role in the maintenance of stem cells throughout development and the rest of human life.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In human embryonic stem cells (hESCs)s, p53 is maintained at low inactive levels.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This is because activation of p53 leads to rapid differentiation of hESCs.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Studies have shown that knocking out p53 delays differentiation and that adding p53 causes spontaneous differentiation, showing how p53 promotes differentiation of hESCs and plays a key role in cell cycle as a differentiation regulator.
[src:oncogenes/p53] When p53 becomes stabilized and activated in hESCs, it increases p21 to establish a longer G1.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This typically leads to abolition of S-phase entry, which stops the cell cycle in G1, leading to differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Work in mouse embryonic stem cells has recently shown however that the expression of P53 does not necessarily lead to differentiation. p53 also activates miR-34a and miR-145, which then repress the hESCs pluripotency factors, further instigating differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In adult stem cells, p53 regulation is important for maintenance of stemness in adult stem cell niches.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Mechanical signals such as hypoxia affect levels of p53 in these niche cells through the hypoxia inducible factors, HIF-1α and HIF-2α.
[src:oncogenes/p53] While HIF-1α stabilizes p53, HIF-2α suppresses it.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Suppression of p53 plays important roles in cancer stem cell phenotype, induced pluripotent stem cells and other stem cell roles and behaviors, such as blastema formation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Cells with decreased levels of p53 have been shown to reprogram into stem cells with a much greater efficiency than normal cells.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Papers suggest that the lack of cell cycle arrest and apoptosis gives more cells the chance to be reprogrammed.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Apart from the cellular and molecular effects above, p53 has a tissue-level anticancer effect that works by inhibiting angiogenesis.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 by regulating Leukemia Inhibitory Factor has been shown to facilitate implantation in the mouse and possibly human reproduction.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The immune response to infection also involves p53 and NF-κB.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Checkpoint control of the cell cycle and of apoptosis by p53 is inhibited by some infections such as Mycoplasma bacteria, raising the specter of oncogenic infection.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Under normal, unstressed conditions, p53 is maintained at low levels through continuous degradation mediated by the E3 ubiquitin ligase MDM2 (HDM2 in humans).
[src:oncogenes/p53] MDM2 binds p53, exports it from the nucleus, and targets it for proteasomal degradation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Notably, p53 transcriptionally activates *MDM2*, establishing a classic negative feedback loop.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This feedback loop gives rise to damped oscillations in p53 levels, as demonstrated both experimentally and in mathematical models.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These oscillations may determine cell fate decisions between survival and apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 is activated in response to a range of cellular stressors, including DNA damage (for example from ultraviolet or ionizing radiation), osmotic shock, ribonucleotide depletion, oncogene activation, and some viral infections.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Activation involves stabilization of the p53 protein, resulting in its accumulation in the nucleus, and regulatory changes that promote sequence-specific DNA binding and transcriptional activation of target genes.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These processes are initiated in part by phosphorylation of residues in the N-terminal transactivation domain by stress-activated kinases.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Phosphorylation of sites within the Mdm2-binding region (for example Ser20) can reduce binding to MDM2 and thereby decrease ubiquitin-mediated degradation of p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Kinases that regulate p53 phosphorylation can be divided into two broad groups.
[src:oncogenes/p53] One group includes members of the MAPK pathways, including JNK1–3, ERK1/2 and p38 MAPK, which are activated by diverse cellular stresses such as oxidative stress and heat shock.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A second group comprises DNA damage response kinases, including ATM, ATR and DNA-PK, together with downstream checkpoint kinases such as CHK1 and CHK2, which are activated by DNA damage and replication stress and contribute to p53 regulation through phosphorylation-dependent signalling.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Additional kinases implicated in p53 phosphorylation include the CDK-activating kinase (CAK; CDK7–cyclin H–MAT1), which has been shown to phosphorylate p53 (for example at Ser33) in vitro and in vivo, and TP53RK (PRPK), which has been reported to phosphorylate p53 at Ser15.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Oncogene-induced activation of p53 can also occur via p14ARF (ARF), which inhibits the p53 antagonist MDM2 and thereby stabilizes p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Several deubiquitinating enzymes (DUBs) modulate p53 stability by removing ubiquitin chains.
[src:oncogenes/p53] USP7, also known as HAUSP, can deubiquitinate both p53 and MDM2.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In unstressed cells, HAUSP preferentially stabilizes MDM2, and its depletion may paradoxically increase p53 levels.
[src:oncogenes/p53] USP42 is another DUB that stabilizes p53 and enhances its ability to respond to stress.
[src:oncogenes/p53] USP10 operates primarily in the cytoplasm, where it counteracts MDM2 by directly deubiquitinating p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] After DNA damage, USP10 translocates to the nucleus and further stabilizes p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Phosphorylation of the N-terminus not only prevents MDM2 binding but also facilitates the recruitment of cofactors.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Pin1 enhances conformational changes in p53, while p300 and PCAF acetylate the C-terminus, exposing the DNA-binding domain and enhancing transcriptional activation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Conversely, deacetylases such as Sirt1 and Sirt7 remove these modifications, suppressing apoptosis and promoting cell survival.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Some oncogenes can also activate p53 indirectly by inhibiting MDM2.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Both experimental evidence and mathematical modeling indicate that p53 levels oscillate over time in response to cellular signals.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These oscillations become more pronounced in the presence of DNA damage, such as double-stranded breaks or UV exposure.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Modeling approaches also help illustrate how mutations in p53 isoforms affect oscillatory behavior, potentially informing tissue-specific therapeutic development.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 function is also influenced by chromatin environment.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The corepressor TRIM24 restricts p53 binding to epigenetically repressed loci by recognizing methylated histones.
[src:oncogenes/p53] This interaction enables p53 to interpret local chromatin context and regulate gene expression in a locus-specific manner.
[src:oncogenes/p53] If the *TP53* gene is damaged, its ability to suppress tumors is severely compromised.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Individuals who inherit only one functional copy of *TP53* are predisposed to developing tumors in early adulthood, a condition known as Li–Fraumeni syndrome.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The *TP53* gene can also be altered by mutagens—such as chemicals, radiation, or certain viruses—thereby increasing the likelihood of uncontrolled cell division.
[src:oncogenes/p53] More than 50 percent of human tumors harbor a mutation or deletion of the *TP53* gene.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Loss of p53 function leads to genomic instability, frequently resulting in an aneuploidy phenotype.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Certain pathogens can also disrupt p53 activity.
[src:oncogenes/p53] For example, human papillomavirus (HPV) produces the viral protein E6, which binds to and inactivates p53.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In conjunction with the HPV protein E7, which inactivates the cell cycle regulator pRb, this promotes repeated cell division, clinically presenting as warts.
[src:oncogenes/p53] High-risk HPV types, particularly types 16 and 18, can drive the progression from benign warts to low- or high-grade cervical dysplasia, reversible precancerous lesions.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Persistent cervical infection can lead to irreversible changes, including carcinoma in situ and invasive cervical cancer.
[src:oncogenes/p53] These outcomes are primarily driven by viral integration into the host genome and the continued expression of the E6 and E7 oncoproteins.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Most p53 mutations are detected by DNA sequencing.
[src:oncogenes/p53] However, it is known that single missense mutations can have a large spectrum from rather mild to very severe functional effects.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The large spectrum of cancer phenotypes due to mutations in the *TP53* gene is also supported by the fact that different isoforms of p53 proteins have different cellular mechanisms for prevention against cancer.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Mutations in *TP53* can give rise to different isoforms, preventing their overall functionality in different cellular mechanisms and thereby extending the cancer phenotype from mild to severe.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Recent studies show that p53 isoforms are differentially expressed in different human tissues, and the loss-of-function or gain-of-function mutations within the isoforms can cause tissue-specific cancer or provide cancer stem cell potential in different tissues.
[src:oncogenes/p53] TP53 mutation also hits energy metabolism and increases glycolysis in breast cancer cells.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A common human polymorphism in *TP53* involves a substitution of arginine for proline at codon 72 of exon 4.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Numerous studies have explored the relationship between this variation and cancer susceptibility, yielding mixed results.
[src:oncogenes/p53] For instance, a 2009 meta-analysis found no association between the codon 72 polymorphism and cervical cancer risk.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Other studies have identified possible associations between the codon 72 polymorphism and various cancers.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A 2011 study reported that the proline variant significantly increased pancreatic cancer risk in males.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Another study found that proline homozygosity was associated with decreased breast cancer risk in Arab women.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Additional research suggested that *TP53* codon 72 polymorphisms, in combination with MDM2 SNP309 and A2164G, may affect susceptibility and age of onset for non-oropharyngeal cancers in women.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A separate 2011 study linked the polymorphism to an increased risk of lung cancer in a Korean population.
[src:oncogenes/p53] However, meta-analyses published in 2011 found no significant associations between the codon 72 variant and risks of either colorectal or endometrial cancer.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A study of a Brazilian birth cohort found an association between the arginine variant and individuals without a family history of cancer.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Meanwhile, another study reported that individuals with the homozygous Pro/Pro genotype had a significantly increased risk of renal cell carcinoma.
[src:oncogenes/p53] While increasing p53 levels might appear beneficial for treating cancer, sustained p53 activation can cause premature aging.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A more promising approach involves restoring normal, endogenous p53 function.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In some tumor types, this leads to regression via apoptosis or normalization of cell growth.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The first commercial gene therapy, Gendicine, was approved in China in 2003 for head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.
[src:oncogenes/p53] It delivers a functional copy of the *TP53* gene using a modified adenovirus.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The small-molecule inhibitor MI-63 can bind to MDM2, blocking its interaction with p53 and reactivating p53 in cancers where its function is suppressed.
[src:oncogenes/p53] A p53 reactivator rezatapopt is in clinical trials in patients whose tumors show the common Y220C mutation of p53, and restores anti-cancer effectiveness to the mutated protein.
[src:oncogenes/p53] p53 was identified in 1979 by Lionel Crawford, David P.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Lane, Arnold Levine, and Lloyd Old, working at Imperial Cancer Research Fund (UK), Princeton University/UMDNJ (Cancer Institute of New Jersey), and Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, respectively.
[src:oncogenes/p53] It had been hypothesized to exist before as the target of the SV40 virus, a strain that induced development of tumors.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The name **p53** is in fact a misnomer, as it describes the apparent molecular mass measured when it was first discovered, though it was later realised this was an overestimate: the correct molecular mass is only 43.7 kDa.
[src:oncogenes/p53] The *TP53* gene from the mouse was first cloned by Peter Chumakov of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR in 1982, and independently in 1983 by Moshe Oren in collaboration with David Givol (Weizmann Institute of Science).
[src:oncogenes/p53] The human *TP53* gene was cloned in 1984 and the full length clone in 1985.
[src:oncogenes/p53] It was initially presumed to be an oncogene due to the use of mutated cDNA following purification of tumor cell mRNA.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Its role as a tumor suppressor gene was revealed in 1989 by Bert Vogelstein at the Johns Hopkins School of Medicine and Arnold Levine at Princeton University. p53 went on to be identified as a transcription factor by Guillermina Lozano working at MD Anderson Cancer Center.
[src:oncogenes/p53] Warren Maltzman, of the Waksman Institute of Rutgers University first demonstrated that TP53 was responsive to DNA damage in the form of ultraviolet radiation.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In a series of publications in 1991–92, Michael Kastan of Johns Hopkins University, reported that TP53 was a critical part of a signal transduction pathway that helped cells respond to DNA damage.
[src:oncogenes/p53] In 1993, p53 was voted *molecule of the year* by *Science* magazine.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] When Ras is 'switched on' by incoming signals, it subsequently switches on other proteins, which ultimately turn on genes involved in cell growth, differentiation, and survival.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Mutations in Ras genes can lead to the production of permanently activated Ras proteins, which can cause unintended and overactive signaling inside the cell, even in the absence of incoming signals.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Because these signals result in cell growth and division, overactive Ras signaling can ultimately lead to cancer.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The three Ras genes in humans (*HRAS*, *KRAS*, and *NRAS*) are the most common oncogenes in human cancer; mutations that permanently activate Ras are found in 20–25% of all human tumors and up to 90% in certain types of cancer (e.g., pancreatic cancer).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] For this reason, Ras inhibitors are being studied as a treatment for cancer and other diseases with Ras overexpression.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The first two Ras genes, *HRAS* and *KRAS*, were identified from studies of two cancer-causing viruses of the *Gammaretrovirus* genus, the Harvey sarcoma virus and Kirsten sarcoma virus, by Edward Scolnick and colleagues at the National Institutes of Health (NIH).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] These viruses were discovered originally in rats during the 1960s by Jennifer Harvey and Werner H.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Kirsten, respectively, hence the name Rat sarcoma.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In 1982, activated and transforming human *ras* genes were discovered in human cancer cells by Geoffrey M.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Cooper at Harvard, Mariano Barbacid and Stuart A.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Aaronson at the NIH, Robert Weinberg at MIT, and Michael Wigler at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] A third *ras* gene was subsequently discovered by researchers in the group of Robin Weiss at the Institute of Cancer Research, and Michael Wigler at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory, named *NRAS*, for its initial identification in human neuroblastoma cells.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The three human *ras* genes encode extremely similar proteins made up of chains of 188 to 189 amino acids.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Their gene symbols are HRAS, NRAS and KRAS, the latter of which produces the K-Ras4A and K-Ras4B isoforms from alternative splicing.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras contains six beta strands and five alpha helices.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G domain contains five G motifs that bind GDP/GTP directly.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G1 motif, or the P-loop, binds the beta phosphate of GDP and GTP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G2 motif, also called Switch I or SW1, contains threonine35, which binds the terminal phosphate (γ-phosphate) of GTP and the divalent magnesium ion bound in the active site.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G3 motif, also called Switch II or SW2, has a DXXGQ motif.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The D is aspartate57, which is specific for guanine versus adenine binding, and Q is glutamine61, the crucial residue that activates a catalytic water molecule for hydrolysis of GTP to GDP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G4 motif contains a LVGNKxDL motif, and provides specific interaction to guanine.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The G5 motif contains a SAK consensus sequence.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The A is alanine146, which provides specificity for guanine rather than adenine.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The two switch motifs, G2 (SW1) and G3 (SW2), are the main parts of the protein that move when GTP is hydrolyzed into GDP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This conformational change by the two switch motifs is what mediates the basic functionality as a molecular switch protein.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This GTP-bound state of Ras is the "on" state, and the GDP-bound state is the "off" state.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The two switch motifs have a number of conformations when binding GTP or GDP or no nucleotide (when bound to SOS1, which releases the nucleotide).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras also binds a magnesium ion which helps to coordinate nucleotide binding.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras proteins function as binary molecular switches that control intracellular signaling networks.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras-regulated signal pathways control such processes as actin cytoskeletal integrity, cell proliferation, cell differentiation, cell adhesion, apoptosis, and cell migration.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras and Ras-related proteins are often deregulated in cancers, leading to increased invasion and metastasis, and decreased apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras activates several pathways, of which the mitogen-activated protein (MAP) kinase cascade has been well-studied.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This cascade transmits signals downstream and results in the transcription of genes involved in cell growth and division.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Another Ras-activated signaling pathway is the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway, which stimulates protein synthesis, cellular migration and growth, and inhibits apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras is a guanosine-nucleotide-binding protein.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Specifically, it is a single-subunit small GTPase, which is related in structure to the Gα subunit of heterotrimeric G proteins (large GTPases).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] G proteins function as binary signaling switches with "on" and "off" states.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In the "off" state it is bound to the nucleotide guanosine diphosphate (GDP), while in the "on" state, Ras is bound to guanosine triphosphate (GTP), which has an extra phosphate group as compared to GDP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This extra phosphate holds the two switch regions in a "loaded-spring" configuration (specifically the Thr-35 and Gly-60).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] When released, the switch regions relax which causes a conformational change into the inactive state.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Hence, activation and deactivation of Ras and other small G proteins are controlled by cycling between the active GTP-bound and inactive GDP-bound forms.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The process of exchanging the bound nucleotide is facilitated by guanine nucleotide exchange factors (GEFs) and GTPase activating proteins (GAPs).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] As per its classification, Ras has an intrinsic GTPase activity, which means that the protein on its own will hydrolyze a bound GTP molecule into GDP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] An inorganic phosphate is released and the Ras molecule is now bound to a GDP.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Since the GDP-bound form is "off" or "inactive" for signaling, GTPase Activating Protein *inactivates* Ras by activating its GTPase activity.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Thus, GAPs accelerate Ras *inactivation*.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] GEFs catalyze a "push and pull" reaction which releases GDP from Ras.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] They insert close to the P-loop and magnesium cation binding site and inhibit the interaction of these with the gamma phosphate anion.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Acidic (negative) residues in switch II "pull" a lysine in the P-loop away from the GDP which "pushes" switch I away from the guanine.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The contacts holding GDP in place are broken and it is released into the cytoplasm.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Because intracellular GTP is abundant relative to GDP (approximately 10 fold more) GTP predominantly re-enters the nucleotide binding pocket of Ras and reloads the spring.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Well known GEFs include Son of Sevenless (Sos) and cdc25 which include the RasGEF domain.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The balance between GEF and GAP activity determines the guanine nucleotide status of Ras, thereby regulating Ras activity.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In the GTP-bound conformation, Ras has a high affinity for numerous effectors which allow it to carry out its functions.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Other small GTPases may bind adaptors such as arfaptin or second messenger systems such as adenylyl cyclase.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The Ras binding domain is found in many effectors and invariably binds to one of the switch regions, because these change conformation between the active and inactive forms.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] However, they may also bind to the rest of the protein surface.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Other proteins exist that may change the activity of Ras family proteins.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] One example is GDI (GDP Disassociation Inhibitor).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] These function by slowing the exchange of GDP for GTP, thus prolonging the inactive state of Ras family members.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Other proteins that augment this cycle may exist.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras is attached to the cell membrane owing to its prenylation and palmitoylation (HRAS and NRAS) or the combination of prenylation and a polybasic sequence adjacent to the prenylation site (KRAS).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The C-terminal CaaX box of Ras first gets farnesylated at its Cys residue in the cytosol, allowing Ras to loosely insert into the membrane of the endoplasmatic reticulum and other cellular membranes.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The Tripeptide (aaX) is then cleaved from the C-terminus by a specific prenyl-protein specific endoprotease and the new C-terminus is methylated by a methyltransferase.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] KRas processing is completed at this stage.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Dynamic electrostatic interactions between its positively charged basic sequence with negative charges at the inner leaflet of the plasma membrane account for its predominant localization at the cell surface at steady-state.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] NRAS and HRAS are further processed on the surface of the Golgi apparatus by palmitoylation of one or two Cys residues, respectively, adjacent to the CaaX box.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The proteins thereby become stably membrane anchored (lipid-rafts) and are transported to the plasma membrane on vesicles of the secretory pathway.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Depalmitoylation by acyl-protein thioesterases eventually releases the proteins from the membrane, allowing them to enter another cycle of palmitoylation and depalmitoylation.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This cycle is believed to prevent the leakage of NRAS and HRAS to other membranes over time and to maintain their steady-state localization along the Golgi apparatus, secretory pathway, plasma membrane and inter-linked endocytosis pathway.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The clinically most notable members of the Ras subfamily are HRAS, KRAS and NRAS, mainly for being implicated in many types of cancer.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Mutations in the Ras family of proto-oncogenes (comprising H-Ras, N-Ras and K-Ras) are very common, being found in 20–30% of all human tumors.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] It is reasonable to speculate that a pharmacological approach that curtails Ras activity may represent a possible method to inhibit certain cancer types.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras point mutations are the single most common abnormality of human proto-oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras inhibitor trans-farnesylthiosalicylic acid (FTS, Salirasib) exhibits profound anti-oncogenic effects in many cancer cell lines.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Inappropriate activation of the gene has been shown to play a key role in improper signal transduction, proliferation and malignant transformation.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Mutations in a number of different genes as well as RAS itself can have this effect.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Oncogenes such as p210BCR-ABL or the growth receptor erbB are upstream of Ras, so if they are constitutively activated their signals will transduce through Ras.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The tumour suppressor gene NF1 encodes a Ras-GAP – its mutation in neurofibromatosis will mean that Ras is less likely to be inactivated.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Ras can also be amplified, although this only occurs occasionally in tumours.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Finally, Ras oncogenes can be activated by point mutations so that the GTPase reaction can no longer be stimulated by GAP – this increases the half life of active Ras-GTP mutants.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The most common mutations are found at residue G12 in the P-loop and the catalytic residue Q61.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] See also "dominant negative" mutants such as S17N and D119N.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Reovirus was noted to be a potential cancer therapeutic when studies suggested it reproduces well in certain cancer cell lines.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] It replicates specifically in cells that have an activated Ras pathway (a cellular signaling pathway that is involved in cell growth and differentiation).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Reovirus replicates in and eventually kills Ras-activated tumour cells and as cell death occurs, progeny virus particles are free to infect surrounding cancer cells.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This cycle of infection, replication and cell death is believed to be repeated until all tumour cells carrying an activated Ras pathway are destroyed.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Another tumor-lysing virus that specifically targets tumor cells with an activated Ras pathway is a type II herpes simplex virus (HSV-2) based agent, designated FusOn-H2.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Activating mutations of the Ras protein and upstream elements of the Ras protein may play a role in more than two-thirds of all human cancers, including most metastatic disease.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Reolysin, a formulation of reovirus, and FusOn-H2 are currently in clinical trials or under development for the treatment of various cancers.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In addition, a treatment based on siRNA anti-mutated K-RAS (G12D) called siG12D LODER is currently in clinical trials for the treatment of locally advanced pancreatic cancer (NCT01188785, NCT01676259).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In glioblastoma mouse models SHP2 levels were heightened in cancerous brain cells.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Inhibiting SHP2 in turn inhibited Ras dephosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This reduced tumor sizes and accompanying rise in survival rates.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Other strategies have attempted to manipulate the regulation of the above-mentioned localization of Ras.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Farnesyltransferase inhibitors have been developed to stop the farnesylation of Ras and therefore weaken its affinity to membranes.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Other inhibitors are targeting the palmitoylation cycle of Ras through inhibiting depalmitoylation by acyl-protein thioesterases, potentially leading to a destabilization of the Ras cycle.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] A 2024 study published in the *International Journal of Molecular Sciences* described a novel inhibitor-finding strategy for mutated Ras molecules.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The Ras mutations in the 12th residue position inhibit the binding of the regulatory GAP molecule to the mutated Ras, causing uncontrolled cell growth.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] The novel strategy proposes finding small glue molecules, which attach the mutated Ras to the GAP, prohibiting uncontrolled cell growth and restoring the normal function.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] For this goal a theoretical Ras-GAP conformation was designed with a several Å gap between the molecules, and a high-throughput in silico docking was performed for finding gluing agents.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] As a proof of concept, two novel molecules were described with satisfying biological activity.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In 2026, the novel RAS inhibitor daraxonrasib completed a phase 3 clinical trial (RASolute 302) to assess efficacy compared to standard-of-care chemotherapy.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] In most of the cell types of most species, most *Ras* is the GDP type.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] This is true for *Xenopus* oocytes and mouse fibroblasts.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] As mentioned above most *X.* oocyte *Ras* is the GDP conjugate.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Mammal *Ras* induces meiosis in *X. laevis* oocytes almost certainly by potentiating insulin-induced meiosis, but not progesterone-induced.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Protein synthesis does not seem to be a part of this step.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Injection increases synthesis of diacylglycerol from phosphatidylcholine.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Some meiosis effects are antagonized by *rap1* (and by a *Ras* modified to dock incorrectly).
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Both *rap1* and the modified *Ras* are co-antagonists with p120Ras GAP in this pathway.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Expressed in all tissues of *Drosophila melanogaster* but mostly in neural cells.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Overexpression is somewhat lethal and, during development, produces eye and wing abnormalities.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] (This parallels - and may be the reason for - similar abnormalities due to mutated receptor tyrosine kinases.) The *D.* genes for *ras*es in mammals produce abnormalities.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Most expression in *Aplysia* spp. is in neural cells.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Also appears to play a role in receptor tyrosine kinase formation in this model.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Overexpression yields a multivulval development due to its involvement in that region's normal development; overexpression in effector sites is lethal.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Essential in *Dictyostelium discoideum*.
[src:oncogenes/ras-protein] Adenylate cyclase activity is unaffected by *ras*.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The **retinoblastoma protein** (protein name abbreviated **Rb** or **pRb**; gene name abbreviated ***Rb***, ***RB*** or ***RB1***) is a tumor suppressor protein that is dysfunctional in several major cancers.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] One function of pRb is to prevent excessive cell growth by inhibiting cell cycle progression until a cell is ready to divide.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] When the cell is ready to divide, pRb is inactivated by phosphorylation, and the cell cycle is allowed to progress.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] It is also a recruiter of several chromatin remodeling enzymes such as methylases and acetylases.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb belongs to the pocket protein family, whose members have a pocket for the functional binding of other proteins.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Should an oncogenic protein, such as those produced by cells infected by high-risk types of human papillomavirus, bind and inactivate pRb, this can lead to cancer.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The *RB* gene may have been responsible for the evolution of multicellularity in several lineages of life including animals.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In humans, the protein is encoded by the *RB1* gene located on chromosome 13—more specifically, 13q14.1-q14.2.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] If both alleles of this gene are mutated in a retinal cell, the protein is inactivated and the cells grow uncontrollably, resulting in development of retinoblastoma, hence the "RB" in the name 'pRb'.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Thus most pRb knock-outs occur in retinal tissue when UV radiation-induced mutation inactivates all healthy copies of the gene, but pRb knock-out has also been documented in certain skin cancers in patients from New Zealand where the amount of UV radiation is significantly higher.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Two forms of retinoblastoma were noticed: a bilateral, familial form and a unilateral, sporadic form.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Sufferers of the former were over six times more likely to develop other types of cancer later in life, compared to individuals with sporadic retinoblastoma.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This highlighted the fact that mutated pRb could be inherited and lent support for the two-hit hypothesis.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This states that only one working allele of a tumour suppressor gene is necessary for its function (the mutated gene is recessive), and so both need to be mutated before the cancer phenotype will appear.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In the familial form, a mutated allele is inherited along with a normal allele.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In this case, should a cell sustain only one mutation in the other *RB* gene, all pRb in that cell would be ineffective at inhibiting cell cycle progression, allowing cells to divide uncontrollably and eventually become cancerous.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Furthermore, as one allele is already mutated in all other somatic cells, the future incidence of cancers in these individuals is observed with linear kinetics.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The working allele need not undergo a mutation per se, as loss of heterozygosity (LOH) is frequently observed in such tumours.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] However, in the sporadic form, both alleles would need to sustain a mutation before the cell can become cancerous.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This explains why sufferers of sporadic retinoblastoma are not at increased risk of cancers later in life, as both alleles are functional in all their other cells.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Future cancer incidence in sporadic pRb cases is observed with polynomial kinetics, not exactly quadratic as expected because the first mutation must arise through normal mechanisms, and then can be duplicated by LOH to result in a tumour progenitor.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb is a multifunctional protein with many binding and phosphorylation sites.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Although its common function is seen as binding and repressing *E2F* targets, pRb is likely a multifunctional protein as it binds to at least 100 other proteins.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb has three major structural components: a carboxy-terminus, a "pocket" subunit, and an amino-terminus.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Within each domain, there are a variety of protein binding sites, as well as a total of 15 possible phosphorylation sites.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Generally, phosphorylation causes interdomain locking, which changes pRb's conformation and prevents binding to target proteins.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Different sites may be phosphorylated at different times, giving rise to many possible conformations and likely many functions/activity levels.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] By keeping E2F-DP inactivated, *RB1* maintains the cell in the G1 phase, preventing progression through the cell cycle and acting as a growth suppressor.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The pRb-E2F/DP complex also attracts a histone deacetylase (HDAC) protein to the chromatin, reducing transcription of S phase promoting factors, further suppressing DNA synthesis.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb has the ability to reversibly inhibit DNA replication through transcriptional repression of DNA replication factors. pRb is able to bind to transcription factors in the E2F family and thereby inhibit their function.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] When pRb is chronically activated, it leads to the downregulation of the necessary DNA replication factors.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Within 72–96 hours of active pRb induction in A2-4 cells, the target DNA replication factor proteins—MCMs, RPA34, DBF4, RFCp37, and RFCp140—all showed decreased levels.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Along with decreased levels, there was a simultaneous and expected inhibition of DNA replication in these cells.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Following induced knockout of pRb, cells treated with cisplatin, a DNA-damaging agent, were able to continue proliferating, without cell cycle arrest, suggesting pRb plays an important role in triggering chronic S-phase arrest in response to genotoxic stress.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] One such example of E2F-regulated genes repressed by pRb are cyclin E and cyclin A.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Both of these cyclins are able to bind to Cdk2 and facilitate entry into the S phase of the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Through the repression of expression of cyclin E and cyclin A, pRb is able to inhibit the G1/S transition.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] There are at least three distinct mechanisms in which pRb can repress transcription of E2F-regulated promoters.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Though these mechanisms are known, it is unclear which are the most important for the control of the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] E2Fs are a family of proteins whose binding sites are often found in the promoter regions of genes for cell proliferation or progression of the cell cycle.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] E2F1 to E2F5 are known to associate with proteins in the pRb-family of proteins while E2F6 and E2F7 are independent of pRb.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Broadly, the E2Fs are split into activator E2Fs and repressor E2Fs though their role is more flexible than that on occasion.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The activator E2Fs are E2F1, E2F2 and E2F3 while the repressor E2Fs are E2F4, E2F5 and E2F6.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Activator E2Fs along with E2F4 bind exclusively to pRb. pRb is able to bind to the activation domain of the activator E2Fs which blocks their activity, repressing transcription of the genes controlled by that E2F-promoter.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The preinitiation complex (PIC) assembles in a stepwise fashion on the promoter of genes to initiate transcription.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The TFIID binds to the TATA box in order to begin the assembly of the TFIIA, recruiting other transcription factors and components needed in the PIC.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Data suggests that pRb is able to repress transcription by both pRb being recruited to the promoter as well as having a target present in TFIID.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The presence of pRb may change the conformation of the TFIIA/IID complex into a less active version with a decreased binding affinity. pRb can also directly interfere with their association as proteins, preventing TFIIA/IID from forming an active complex.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb acts as a recruiter that allows for the binding of proteins that alter chromatin structure onto the site E2F-regulated promoters.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Access to these E2F-regulated promoters by transcriptional factors is blocked by the formation of nucleosomes and their further packing into chromatin.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Nucleosome formation is regulated by post-translational modifications to histone tails.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Acetylation leads to the disruption of nucleosome structure.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Proteins called histone acetyltransferases (HATs) are responsible for acetylating histones and thus facilitating the association of transcription factors on DNA promoters.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Deacetylation, on the other hand, leads to nucleosome formation and thus makes it more difficult for transcription factors to sit on promoters.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Histone deacetylases (HDACs) are the proteins responsible for facilitating nucleosome formation and are therefore associated with transcriptional repressors proteins.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb interacts with the histone deacetylases HDAC1 and HDAC3. pRb binds to HDAC1 in its pocket domain in a region that is independent to its E2F-binding site. pRb recruitment of histone deacetylases leads to the repression of genes at E2F-regulated promoters due to nucleosome formation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Some genes activated during the G1/S transition such as cyclin E are repressed by HDAC during early to mid-G1 phase.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This suggests that HDAC-assisted repression of cell cycle progression genes is crucial for the ability of pRb to arrest cells in G1.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] To further add to this point, the HDAC-pRb complex is shown to be disrupted by cyclin D/Cdk4 which levels increase and peak during the late G1 phase.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] For example, pRb was detected on the cyclin A and PCNA promoters in senescent cells.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Cells respond to stress in the form of DNA damage, activated oncogenes, or sub-par growing conditions, and can enter a senescence-like state called "premature senescence".
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This allows the cell to prevent further replication during periods of damaged DNA or general unfavorable conditions.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] DNA damage in a cell can induce pRb activation. pRb's role in repressing the transcription of cell cycle progression genes leads to the S phase arrest that prevents replication of damaged DNA.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] When it is time for a cell to enter S phase, complexes of cyclin-dependent kinases (CDK) and cyclins phosphorylate pRb, allowing E2F-DP to dissociate from pRb and become active.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Since the 1990s, pRb was known to be inactivated via phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Until, the prevailing model was that Cyclin D- Cdk 4/6 progressively phosphorylated it from its unphosphorylated to its hyperphosphorylated state (14+ phosphorylations).
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] However, it was recently shown that pRb only exists in three states: un-phosphorylated, mono-phosphorylated, and hyper-phosphorylated.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Before the development of 2D IEF, only hyper-phosphorylated pRb was distinguishable from all other forms, i.e. un-phosphorylated pRb resembled mono-phosphorylated pRb on immunoblots.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] As pRb was either in its active "hypo-phosphorylated" state or inactive "hyperphosphorylated" state.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] However, with 2D IEF, it is now known that pRb is un-phosphorylated in G0 cells and mono-phosphorylated in early G1 cells, prior to hyper-phosphorylation after the restriction point in late G1.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] When a cell enters G1, Cyclin D- Cdk4/6 phosphorylates pRb at a single phosphorylation site.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] No progressive phosphorylation occurs because when HFF cells were exposed to sustained cyclin D- Cdk4/6 activity (and even deregulated activity) in early G1, only mono-phosphorylated pRb was detected.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Furthermore, triple knockout, p16 addition, and Cdk 4/6 inhibitor addition experiments confirmed that Cyclin D- Cdk 4/6 is the sole phosphorylator of pRb.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Throughout early G1, mono-phosphorylated pRb exists as 14 different isoforms (the 15th phosphorylation site is not conserved in primates in which the experiments were performed).
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Together, these isoforms represent the "hypo-phosphorylated" active pRb state that was thought to exist.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Each isoform has distinct preferences to associate with different exogenous expressed E2Fs.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] A recent report showed that mono-phosphorylation controls pRb's association with other proteins and generates functional distinct forms of pRb.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] All different mono-phosphorylated pRb isoforms inhibit E2F transcriptional program and are able to arrest cells in G1-phase.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Importantly, different mono-phosphorylated forms of pRb have distinct transcriptional outputs that are extended beyond E2F regulation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] After a cell passes the restriction point, Cyclin E - Cdk 2 hyper-phosphorylates all mono-phosphorylated isoforms.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] While the exact mechanism is unknown, one hypothesis is that binding to the C-terminus tail opens the pocket subunit, allowing access to all phosphorylation sites.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This process is hysteretic and irreversible, and it is thought accumulation of mono-phosphorylated pRb induces the process.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Presence of un-phosphorylated pRb drives cell cycle exit and maintains senescence.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] At the end of mitosis, PP1 dephosphorylates hyper-phosphorylated pRb directly to its un-phosphorylated state.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Furthermore, when cycling C2C12 myoblast cells differentiated (by being placed into a differentiation medium), only un-phosphorylated pRb was present.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Additionally, these cells had a markedly decreased growth rate and concentration of DNA replication factors (suggesting G0 arrest).
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This function of un-phosphorylated pRb gives rise to a hypothesis for the lack of cell cycle control in cancerous cells: Deregulation of Cyclin D - Cdk 4/6 phosphorylates un-phosphorylated pRb in senescent cells to mono-phosphorylated pRb, causing them to enter G1.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The mechanism of the switch for Cyclin E activation is not known, but one hypothesis is that it is a metabolic sensor.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Mono-phosphorylated pRb induces an increase in metabolism, so the accumulation of mono-phosphorylated pRb in previously G0 cells then causes hyper-phosphorylation and mitotic entry.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Since any un-phosphorylated pRb is immediately phosphorylated, the cell is then unable to exit the cell cycle, resulting in continuous division.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] DNA damage to G0 cells activates Cyclin D - Cdk 4/6, resulting in mono-phosphorylation of un-phosphorylated pRb.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Then, active mono-phosphorylated pRb causes repression of E2F-targeted genes specifically.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Therefore, mono-phosphorylated pRb is thought to play an active role in DNA damage response, so that E2F gene repression occurs until the damage is fixed and the cell can pass the restriction point.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] As a side note, the discovery that damages causes Cyclin D - Cdk 4/6 activation even in G0 cells should be kept in mind when patients are treated with both DNA damaging chemotherapy and Cyclin D - Cdk 4/6 inhibitors.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] During the M-to-G1 transition, pRb is then progressively dephosphorylated by PP1, returning to its growth-suppressive hypophosphorylated state.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb family proteins are components of the DREAM complex composed of DP, E2F4/5, RB-like (p130/p107) And MuvB (Lin9:Lin37:Lin52:RbAbP4:Lin54).
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The DREAM complex is assembled in Go/G1 and maintains quiescence by assembling at the promoters of > 800 cell-cycle genes and mediating transcriptional repression.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Assembly of DREAM requires DYRK1A (Ser/Thr kinase) dependant phosphorylation of the MuvB core component, Lin52 at Serine28.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This mechanism is crucial for recruitment of p130/p107 to the MuvB core and thus DREAM assembly.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Consequences of loss of pRb function is dependent on cell type and cell cycle status, as pRb's tumor suppressive role changes depending on the state and current identity of the cell.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In G0 quiescent stem cells, pRb is proposed to maintain G0 arrest although the mechanism remains largely unknown.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Loss of pRb leads to exit from quiescence and an increase in the number of cells without loss of cell renewal capacity.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In cycling progenitor cells, pRb plays a role at the G1, S, and G2 checkpoints and promotes differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In differentiated cells, which make up the majority of cells in the body and are assumed to be in irreversible G0, pRb maintains both arrest and differentiation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Loss of pRb therefore exhibits multiple different responses within different cells that ultimately all could result in cancer phenotypes.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] For cancer initiation, loss of pRb may induce cell cycle re-entry in both quiescent and post-mitotic differentiated cells through dedifferentiation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In cancer progression, loss of pRb decreases the differentiating potential of cycling cells, increases chromosomal instability, prevents induction of cellular senescence, promotes angiogenesis, and increases metastatic potential.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Although most cancers rely on glycolysis for energy production (Warburg effect), cancers due to pRb loss tend to upregulate oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The increased oxidative phosphorylation can increase stemness, metastasis, and (when enough oxygen is available) cellular energy for anabolism.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The classic view of pRb's role as a tumor suppressor and cell cycle regulator developed through research investigating mechanisms of interactions with E2F family member proteins.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Yet, more data generated from biochemical experiments and clinical trials reveal other functions of pRb within the cell unrelated (or indirectly related) to tumor suppression.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Studies have also demonstrated that hyperphosphorylated pRb can specifically bind E2F1 and form stable complexes throughout the cell cycle to carry out unique unexplored functions, a surprising contrast from the classical view of pRb releasing E2F factors upon phosphorylation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In summary, many new findings about pRb's resistance to CDK phosphorylation are emerging in pRb research and shedding light on novel roles of pRb beyond cell cycle regulation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb is able to be localize to sites of DNA breaks during the repair process and assist in non-homologous end joining and homologous recombination through complexing with E2F1.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Once at the breaks, pRb is able to recruit regulators of chromatin structure such as the DNA helicase transcription activator BRG1. pRb has been shown to also be able to recruit protein complexes such as condensin and cohesin to assist in the structural maintenance of chromatin.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Such findings suggest that in addition to its tumor suppressive role with E2F, pRb is also distributed throughout the genome to aid in important processes of genome maintenance such as DNA break-repair, DNA replication, chromosome condensation, and heterochromatin formation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] pRb has also been implicated in regulating metabolism through interactions with components of cellular metabolic pathways.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] RB1 mutations can cause alterations in metabolism, including reduced mitochondrial respiration, reduced activity in the electron transport chain, and changes in flux of glucose and/or glutamine.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Particular forms of pRb have been found to localize to the outer mitochondrial membrane and directly interacts with Bax to promote apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This focus has resulted in the recent development and FDA clinical approval of three small molecule CDK4/6 inhibitors (palbociclib (Ibrance, Pfizer 2015), ribociclib (Kisqali, Novartis 2017), and abemaciclib (Verzenio, Eli Lilly 2017) for the treatment of specific breast cancer subtypes.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Treatment of cancers by CDK4/6 inhibitors depends on the presence of pRb within the cell for therapeutic effect, limiting their usage only to cancers where RB is not mutated and pRb protein levels are not significantly depleted.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Direct pRb reactivation in humans has not been achieved.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Reactivation of pRb in these mice rescues the tumors towards a less metastatic state, but does not completely stop tumor growth due to a proposed rewiring of MAPK pathway signaling, which suppresses pRb through a CDK-dependent mechanism.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Besides trying to re-activate the tumor suppressive function of pRb, one other distinct approach to treat dysregulated pRb pathway cancers is to take advantage of certain cellular consequences induced by pRb loss.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] It has been shown that E2F stimulates expression of pro-apoptotic genes in addition to G1/S transition genes, however, cancer cells have developed defensive signaling pathways that protect themselves from death by deregulated E2F activity.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Development of inhibitors of these protective pathways could thus be a synthetically lethal method to kill cancer cells with overactive E2F.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In addition, it has been shown that the pro-apoptotic activity of p53 is restrained by the pRb pathway, such that pRb deficient tumor cells become sensitive to p53 mediated cell death.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This opens the door to research of compounds that could activate p53 activity in these cancer cells and induce apoptosis and reduce cell proliferation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] While the loss of a tumor suppressor such as pRb leading to uncontrolled cell proliferation is detrimental in the context of cancer, it may be beneficial to deplete or inhibit suppressive functions of pRb in the context of cellular regeneration.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Harvesting the proliferative abilities of cells induced to a controlled "cancer like" state could aid in repairing damaged tissues and delay aging phenotypes.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] This idea remains to be thoroughly explored as a potential cellular injury and anti-aging treatment.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The retinoblastoma protein is involved in the growth and development of mammalian hair cells of the cochlea, and appears to be related to the cells' inability to regenerate.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Embryonic hair cells require pRb, among other important proteins, to exit the cell-cycle and stop dividing, which allows maturation of the auditory system.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Once wild-type mammals have reached adulthood, their cochlear hair cells become incapable of proliferation.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In studies where the gene for pRb is deleted in mice cochlea, hair cells continue to proliferate in early adulthood.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Though this may seem to be a positive development, pRb-knockdown mice tend to develop severe hearing loss due to degeneration of the organ of Corti.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] For this reason, pRb seems to be instrumental for completing the development of mammalian hair cells and keeping them alive.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] However, it is clear that without pRb, hair cells have the ability to proliferate, which is why pRb is known as a tumor suppressor.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Temporarily and precisely turning off pRb in adult mammals with damaged hair cells may lead to propagation and therefore successful regeneration.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Suppressing function of the retinoblastoma protein in the adult rat cochlea has been found to cause proliferation of supporting cells and hair cells. pRb can be downregulated by activating the sonic hedgehog pathway, which phosphorylates the proteins and reduces gene transcription.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Disrupting pRb expression in vitro, either by gene deletion or knockdown of pRb short interfering RNA, causes dendrites to branch out farther.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] In addition, Schwann cells, which provide essential support for the survival of neurons, travel with the neurites, extending farther than normal.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] The inhibition of pRb supports the continued growth of nerve cells.
[src:oncogenes/retinoblastoma-protein] Several methods for detecting the RB1 gene mutations have been developed including a method that can detect large deletions that correlate with advanced stage retinoblastoma.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] A **tumor suppressor gene** (**TSG**), or **anti-oncogene**, is a gene that regulates a cell during cell division and replication.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] When a tumor suppressor gene is mutated, it results in a loss or reduction in its function.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In combination with other genetic mutations, this could allow the cell to grow abnormally.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The loss of function for these genes may be even more significant in the development of human cancers, compared to the activation of oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] TSGs can be grouped into the following categories: caretaker genes, gatekeeper genes, and more recently landscaper genes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Caretaker genes ensure stability of the genome via DNA repair and subsequently when mutated allow mutations to accumulate.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Meanwhile, gatekeeper genes directly regulate cell growth by either inhibiting cell cycle progression or inducing apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Lastly, landscaper genes regulate growth by contributing to the surrounding environment, and when mutated, can cause an environment that promotes unregulated proliferation.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The classification schemes are evolving as medical advances are being made from fields including molecular biology, genetics, and epigenetics.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The discovery of oncogenes and their ability to deregulate cellular processes related to cell proliferation and development appeared first in the literature as opposed to the idea of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] However, the idea of genetic mutation leading to increased tumor growth gave way to another possible genetic idea of genes playing a role in decreasing cellular growth and development of cells.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This idea was not solidified until experiments by Henry Harris were conducted with somatic cell hybridization in 1969.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Within Harris's experiments, tumor cells were fused with normal somatic cells to make hybrid cells.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Each cell had chromosomes from both parents and upon growth, a majority of these hybrid cells did not have the capability of developing tumors within animals.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The suppression of tumorigenicity in these hybrid cells prompted researchers to hypothesize that genes within the normal somatic cell had inhibitory actions to stop tumor growth.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This initial hypothesis eventually lead to the discovery of the first classic tumor suppressor gene by Alfred Knudson, known as the Rb gene, which codes for the retinoblastoma tumor suppressor protein.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Alfred Knudson, a pediatrician and cancer geneticist, proposed that in order to develop retinoblastoma, two allelic mutations are required to lose functional copies of both the Rb genes to lead to tumorigenicity.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Knudson observed that retinoblastoma often developed early in life for younger patients in both eyes, while in some rarer cases retinoblastoma would develop later in life and only be unilateral.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The more sporadic occurrence of unilateral development of retinoblastoma was hypothesized to develop much later in life due to two de novo mutations that were needed to fully lose tumor suppressor properties.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This finding formed the basis of the two-hit hypothesis.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In order to verify that the loss of function of tumor suppressor genes causes increased tumorigenicity, interstitial deletion experiments on chromosome 13q14 were conducted to observe the effect of deleting the loci for the Rb gene.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This deletion caused increased tumor growth in retinoblastoma, suggesting that loss or inactivation of a tumor suppressor gene can increase tumorigenicity.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Unlike oncogenes, tumor suppressor genes generally follow the two-hit hypothesis, which states both alleles that code for a particular protein must be affected before an effect is manifested.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] If only one allele for the gene is damaged, the other can still produce enough of the correct protein to retain the appropriate function.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In other words, mutant tumor suppressor alleles are usually recessive, whereas mutant oncogene alleles are typically dominant.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] He observed that 40% of U.S cases were caused by a mutation in the germ-line.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] However, affected parents could have children without the disease, but the unaffected children became parents of children with retinoblastoma.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This indicates that one could inherit a mutated germ-line but not display the disease.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Knudson observed that the age of onset of retinoblastoma followed 2nd order kinetics, implying that two independent genetic events were necessary.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] He recognized that this was consistent with a recessive mutation involving a single gene, but requiring bi-allelic mutation.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Hereditary cases involve an inherited mutation and a single mutation in the normal allele.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Non-hereditary retinoblastoma involves two mutations, one on each allele.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Knudson also noted that hereditary cases often developed bilateral tumors and would develop them earlier in life, compared to non-hereditary cases where individuals were only affected by a single tumor.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] There are exceptions to the two-hit rule for tumor suppressors, such as certain mutations in the p53 gene product. p53 mutations can function as a dominant negative, meaning that a mutated p53 protein can prevent the function of the natural protein produced from the non-mutated allele.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Other tumor-suppressor genes that do not follow the two-hit rule are those that exhibit haploinsufficiency, including PTCH in medulloblastoma and NF1 in neurofibroma.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Another example is p27, a cell-cycle inhibitor, that when one allele is mutated causes increased carcinogen susceptibility.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The proteins encoded by most tumor suppressor genes inhibit cell proliferation or survival.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Inactivation of tumor suppressor genes therefore leads to tumor development by eliminating negative regulatory proteins.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In most cases, tumor suppressor proteins inhibit the same cell regulatory pathways that are stimulated by the products of oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Receptors or signal transducers for secreted hormones or developmental signals that inhibit cell proliferation (e.g., transforming growth factor (TGF)-β and adenomatous polyposis coli (APC)).
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Checkpoint-control proteins that trigger cell cycle arrest in response to DNA damage or chromosomal defects (e.g., breast cancer type 1 susceptibility protein (BRCA1), p16, and p14).
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] If damage cannot be repaired, the cell initiates programmed cell death to remove the threat it poses to the organism as a whole.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Some proteins involved in cell adhesion prevent tumor cells from dispersing, block loss of contact inhibition, and inhibit metastasis.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] These proteins are known as metastasis suppressors.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Proteins involved in repairing mistakes in DNA.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Caretaker genes encode proteins that function in repairing mutations in the genome, preventing cells from replicating with mutations.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Furthermore, increased mutation rate from decreased DNA repair leads to increased inactivation of other tumor suppressors and activation of oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] (e.g., p53 and DNA mismatch repair protein 2 (MSH2)).
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Certain genes can also act as tumor suppressors and oncogenes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Dubbed Proto-oncogenes with Tumor suppressor function, these genes act as "double agents" that both positively and negatively regulate transcription.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Expression of genes, including tumor suppressors, can be altered through biochemical alterations known as DNA methylation.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Methylation is an example of epigenetic modifications, which commonly regulate expression in mammalian genes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The addition of a methyl group to either histone tails or directly on DNA causes the nucleosome to pack tightly together restricting the transcription of any genes in this region.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This process not only has the capabilities to inhibit gene expression, it can also increase the chance of mutations.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Stephen Baylin observed that if promoter regions experience a phenomenon known as hypermethylation, it could result in later transcriptional errors, tumor suppressor gene silencing, protein misfolding, and eventually cancer growth.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Baylin et al. found methylation inhibitors known as azacitidine and decitabine.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] These compounds can actually help prevent cancer growth by inducing re-expression of previously silenced genes, arresting the cell cycle of the tumor cell and forcing it into apoptosis.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] There are further clinical trials under current investigation regarding treatments for hypermethylation as well as alternate tumor suppression therapies that include prevention of tissue hyperplasia, tumor development, or metastatic spread of tumors.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The team working with Wajed have investigated neoplastic tissue methylation in order to one day identify early treatment options for gene modification that can silence the tumor suppressor gene.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In addition to DNA methylation, other epigenetic modifications like histone deacetylation or chromatin-binding proteins can prevent DNA polymerase from effectively transcribing desired sequences, such as ones containing tumor suppressor genes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Gene therapy is used to reinstate the function of a mutated or deleted gene type.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] When tumor suppressor genes are altered in a way that results in less or no expression, several severe problems can arise for the host.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This is why tumor suppressor genes have commonly been studied and used for gene therapy.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The two main approaches used currently to introduce genetic material into cells are viral and non-viral delivery methods.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The viral method of transferring genetic material harnesses the power of viruses.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] By using viruses that are durable to genetic material alterations, viral methods of gene therapy for tumor suppressor genes have shown to be successful.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In this method, vectors from viruses are used.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The two most commonly used vectors are adenoviral vectors and adeno-associated vectors.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In vitro genetic manipulation of these types of vectors is easy and in vivo application is relatively safe compared to other vectors.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Before the vectors are inserted into the tumors of the host, they are prepared by having the parts of their genome that control replication either mutated or deleted.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Then, the desired genetic material is inserted and ligated to the vector.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In the case with tumor suppressor genes, genetic material which encodes p53 has been used successfully, which after application, has shown reduction in tumor growth or proliferation.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The non-viral method of transferring genetic material is used less often than the viral method.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] However, the non-viral method is a more cost-effective, safer, available method of gene delivery not to mention that non-viral methods have shown to induce fewer host immune responses and possess no restrictions on size or length of the transferable genetic material.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Non-viral gene therapy uses either chemical or physical methods to introduce genetic material to the desired cells.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The chemical methods are used primarily for tumor suppressor gene introduction and are divided into two categories which are naked plasmid or liposome-coated plasmids.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The naked plasmid strategy has garnered interest because of its easy-to-use methods.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Direct injection into the muscles allows for the plasmid to be taken up into the cell of possible tumors where the genetic material of the plasmid can be incorporated into the genetic material of the tumor cells and revert any previous damage done to tumor suppressor genes.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The liposome-coated plasmid method has recently also been of interest since they produce relatively low host immune response and are efficient with cellular targeting.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The positively charged capsule in which the genetic material is packaged helps with electrostatic attraction to the negatively charged membranes of the cells as well as the negatively charged DNA of the tumor cells.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] In this way, non-viral methods of gene therapy are highly effective in restoring tumor suppressor gene function to tumor cells that have either partially or entirely lost this function.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The viral and non-viral gene therapies mentioned above are commonly used but each has some limitations which must be considered.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] The most important limitation these methods have is the efficacy at which the adenoviral and adeno-associated vectors, naked plasmids, or liposome-coated plasmids are taken in by the host's tumor cells.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] If proper uptake by the host's tumor cells is not achieved, re-insertion introduces problems such as the host's immune system recognizing these vectors or plasmids and destroying them which impairs the overall effectiveness of the gene therapy treatment further.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] As the cost of DNA sequencing continues to diminish, more cancers can be sequenced.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] This allows for the discovery of novel tumor suppressors and can give insight on how to treat and cure different cancers in the future.
[src:oncogenes/tumor-suppressor-gene] Other examples of tumor suppressors include pVHL, APC, CD95, ST5, YPEL3, ST7, and ST14, p16, BRCA2.
